narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: Making digital photographs; using Photoshop to edit pictures; printing digital photographs using inkjet; self-evaluating my work and progress; evaluating the work and progress of peers; discussing photographs from aesthetic, technical, historical, and ethical perspectives.
I improved my photography skills and my command over my DSLR. This course taught me the basics of using my camera, which in turn helped me execute my artistic vision well.

I learned how to look at photos and appreciate them, also the names of many photographers. I learned how to take and frame photos and which are the most successful. I also learned about different camera settings and how to use photoshop.
Learn camera basics (aperture, shutter speed, white balance, etc.), image editing in photoshop, and how to make a print portfolio with a theme in mind
I gained a lot more knowledge about the process of digital photography and editing, as well as an appreciation for a wide range of work from other photographers.
Basic use of Adobe Photoshop and Bridge, printing, thinking about photography in a more critical / engaging way as someone with limited photography experience

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments:
Strengths: structure was loose enough to allow students to explore interests while retaining a technical edge that equipped those new to photography with the skills necessary to improve their photography skills and eye; Ted is an incredible professor who challenges students

Weaknesses: n/a
Professor Partin was a fantastic professor. He was very encouraging while also pushing us. I also appreciated having access to the lab to edit and print my photos.
The course is wide open in terms of your focus. This can be good or bad, but for me it was really refreshing. I did sometimes wish it had more structure to motivate me to shoot more often.

Strengths: I really love the open-endedness of the course and how chill Ted was with our critiques, I had a lot of fun just messing around with photos and didn't often feel like I was doing work for the class because it was fun
Weaknesses: You have to pay a $150 course fee + the cost of printing materials ($70 retail for the recommended pack) and secure your own dslr camera if you don't already have one; but I say it's completely worth it if you know you are going to be engaged with the class

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes! Ted is an amazing professor and the class is stimulating and beneficial whether you have a background in photography or if this is your first photo class

Yes! Regardless of your major or interests, taking this course truly exposed me to new questions about the medium of photography as it relates to identity, politics, history, etc. Ted is such a great instructor!

Yes! It is very different from other courses in the sense that your work is in the form of photographs, not assignments or exams. It helped me get out and about in New Haven, exploring new parts of the city, while also giving me a creative outlet. Would recommend!

Yes, I would absolutely recommend this course to another student. It was so different from most other classes I've taken at Yale in a good way. I think every student should take a course like this before graduating.
For sure! If you are new to photography and want to explore photography more from either a technical or artistic point of view, this class is a great first step
I certainly recommend to any students who have limited experience and are looking to learn the basics of digital photography.
Yes, if you can take this course do it! Ted is such a great professor and really cares for his students
